Neotoma Resources with Seminole Cultural Affiliation

April 2024

Introduction

This page will briefly survey paleoecological records from sites with Choctaw cultural affiliation held by the Neotoma Paleoecology Database. This page was created by Nick Hoffman, as a project for the Ethical Open Science Research Coordination Network (EOS RCN).The leader of the EOS RCN is Jessica Blois, Professor at UC-Merced. If you would like to explore these records or other Neotoma data further, we are happy to help with that, so please reach out to either of us at nicholashoffman@ucmerced.edu or jblois@ucmerced.edu.

About Neotoma

Neotoma was formed in 2006 as a federated database constituted by a set of more specialized paleoecological databases. This means that Neotoma brings together paleoecological data from a range of proxy types (e.g., pollen, charcoal, testate amoebae), regions (e.g., North America, Latin America, Europe), and time periods (e.g., Pliocene, Pleistocene, Holocene). Neotoma incorporates data collected over more than 150 years.

Neotoma and Native Lands

Neotoma contains records from upwards of 22,000 sites. Many of these sites are affiliated with native lands. A subset of these sites comes from federally recognized reservations in the United States.

The following table counts the number of sites (n) from Neotoma that fall within the borders of federally recognized reservations. Overall, there are 692 sites on 105 reservations. Florida has many Neotoma sites.

Neotoma Resources in Florida

The following map shows the location of Neotoma sites in Florida. There are (as of April 2024) 432 distinct sites, but some of them may be close together, so 432 dots are not necessarily distinguishable on the map. Also be aware that there may be points on the coast of Florida that arent captured within the borders of the Florida polygon used on this page. Overlaid on this map are lands protected by the top five biggest land managers in Florida (Forest Service; Regional Water Districts; State Fish and Wildlife; Other state; and National Park Service).

And the following table lists some information about those sites.

We can further inspect the sites by the kinds of data they contain. Neotoma sites in Florida concern pollen, vertebrate fauna, diatom, water chemistry, macroinvertebrate, loss-on-ignition, charcoal, X-ray fluorescence (XRF), biomarker, geochemistry, insect and plant macrofossil. The following map shows the distribution of Neotoma datasets by dataset type for the top five most abundant dataset types in Florida.

Physical specimens are not typically preserved for all types of datasets, and Neotoma doesnt have perfect information about the disposition of the physical specimens even when they do exist. What we do know is that for Neotoma data collected from Florida, the Florida Museum of Natural History, Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, University of Florida, Florida State Museum, American Museum of Natural History, National Museum of Natural History and University of South Florida hold physical specimens.
